context: A cricket pitch is 22 yards (20.12 meters) long.
A cricket team consists of 11 players.
A batsman in cricket tries to score runs by hitting the ball and running between the wickets.
An over consists of six legal deliveries bowled by a bowler.
A wicket refers to the three stumps and two bails, and also to the act of dismissing a batsman.
The basic equipment in cricket includes a bat, ball, stumps, pads, gloves, and helmet.
A century is when a batsman scores 100 runs in a single innings.
A duck refers to a batsman getting out without scoring any runs.
A boundary is scored when the ball hits the boundary rope or goes over it, awarding four or six runs.
There are fast bowlers, medium pace bowlers, and spin bowlers in cricket.
A no-ball is an illegal delivery, usually due to overstepping the crease or bowling a high full toss.
A wide ball is an illegal delivery bowled outside the batsman's reach.
LBW stands for Leg Before Wicket, a mode of dismissal where the ball hits the batsman's leg before hitting the bat, and would have hit the stumps.
A Test match is the longest format of cricket, played over five days with unlimited overs.
An ODI is a limited-overs format of cricket, played over 50 overs per side.
A T20 match is a short format of cricket, played over 20 overs per side.
A wicketkeeper stands behind the stumps to catch the ball if the batsman misses it and to perform stumping.
A maiden over is an over in which no runs are scored.
A hat-trick occurs when a bowler takes three wickets with three consecutive deliveries.
The Ashes is a Test cricket series played between England and Australia.
The ICC, or International Cricket Council, is the global governing body for cricket.
A yorker is a delivery bowled at the batsman's feet, aiming to hit the stumps or restrict runs.
A bouncer is a short-pitched delivery that rises towards the batsman's head or chest.
A spinner is a bowler who uses spin to deceive the batsman, typically bowling at a slower pace.
A fast bowler bowls at high speeds, usually over 90 mph (145 km/h), relying on pace and bounce.
A googly is a type of delivery bowled by a leg-spinner that spins in the opposite direction to a normal leg break.
A run out occurs when a fielder hits the stumps with the ball while the batsmen are running between the wickets.
A stumping is a dismissal by the wicketkeeper who removes the bails while the batsman is out of their crease.
A powerplay is a period in limited-overs cricket with fielding restrictions, allowing only a few fielders outside the 30-yard circle.
A follow-on is enforced when the team batting second scores significantly fewer runs than the team batting first, requiring them to bat again immediately.
A declaration occurs when the batting team voluntarily ends their innings, usually to try and force a result in a Test match.
A dead ball is a period when the ball is not in play and no runs can be scored or wickets taken.
The DRS, or Decision Review System, allows players to request a review of the umpire's decision using technology.
An umpire is responsible for making decisions on the field, such as dismissals and boundary calls.
A six is scored when the batsman hits the ball over the boundary on the full.
A four is scored when the batsman hits the ball and it reaches the boundary, touching the ground at least once.
A single is when the batsman runs one run between the wickets.
A strike rate measures how quickly a batsman scores runs or how effective a bowler is at taking wickets.
The Duckworth-Lewis method is a mathematical formula used to calculate target scores in rain-affected limited-overs matches.
A nightwatchman is a lower-order batsman sent in to bat near the end of the day in Test matches to protect more skilled batsmen.
A free hit is awarded after a no-ball, allowing the batsman to score without the risk of getting out by most means.
A cover drive is a batting shot played with a straight bat through the cover region.
A reverse sweep is a shot where the batsman sweeps the ball in the opposite direction to a normal sweep shot.
A leg glance is a shot played with a light touch, directing the ball towards the leg side.
A pull shot is played to a short-pitched delivery, hitting the ball towards the leg side.
A hook shot is played to a bouncer, hitting the ball towards the leg side, usually in the air.
A square cut is a shot played to a short, wide delivery, hitting the ball square on the off side.
Short leg is a fielding position close to the batsman on the leg side, usually for catching.
Silly point is a fielding position very close to the batsman on the off side, often for catching.
Third man is a fielding position behind the wicket on the off side, near the boundary.
Fine leg is a fielding position behind the wicket on the leg side, near the boundary.
Mid-on is a fielding position close to the bowler on the leg side.
Mid-off is a fielding position close to the bowler on the off side.
Long-on is a fielding position on the boundary straight behind the bowler on the leg side.
Long-off is a fielding position on the boundary straight behind the bowler on the off side.
The captain leads the team, makes tactical decisions, and represents the team in discussions with the umpires.
A declaration is when the batting captain decides to end their innings voluntarily to try to win the match.
A follow-through is the motion a bowler goes through after delivering the ball.
A part-time bowler is a player who usually bats or fields, but occasionally bowls.
A specialist batsman focuses primarily on batting and is selected for their batting skills.
A specialist bowler focuses primarily on bowling and is selected for their bowling skills.
An all-rounder is a player who excels in both batting and bowling.
An innings is a period in which a team takes its turn to bat.
A session is one of the three periods of play in a day's play of a Test match.
A delivery is a single ball bowled by the bowler to the batsman.
The crease is a set of lines on the cricket pitch where the batsman stands and where the bowler delivers the ball from.
A run chase is when the batting team tries to reach the target set by the opposition.
A draw occurs when a Test match ends without a result after five days of play.
A tie occurs when both teams score the same number of runs and all innings are completed.
A spinner's main strategy is to deceive the batsman with variations in spin, flight, and speed.
A fast bowler's main strategy is to use speed, bounce, and seam movement to dismiss batsmen.
A fielder's role is to stop the ball, prevent runs, and dismiss batsmen by catching or running them out.
A Test match day is typically comprised of three sessions of play, each lasting around two hours.
The drinks break allows players to hydrate and regroup, usually occurring midway through a session.
The coin toss determines which team will bat or bowl first in a match.
Clean bowled means the batsman is dismissed by the ball hitting the stumps directly without touching the bat.
A short-pitched delivery bounces early and rises towards the batsman, often used to intimidate or create catching opportunities.
A half-volley is a delivery that bounces just short of the batsman's feet, making it easier to drive.
A full toss is a delivery that reaches the batsman without bouncing, making it easier to hit.
A dot ball is a delivery where no run is scored and the batsman is not dismissed.
A partnership is the number of runs scored while two batsmen are at the crease together.
A collapse is when several wickets fall in quick succession, often leading to a lower team total.
A declaration is when the batting team voluntarily ends their innings to try and force a result.
A coach trains the players, plans strategies, and provides guidance during matches.
A pinch hitter is a lower-order batsman promoted up the order to score quick runs.
The primary objective of the batting team is to score as many runs as possible.
The primary objective of the bowling team is to dismiss the batsmen and restrict runs.
An off-spinner spins the ball from off to leg side for a right-handed batsman, while a leg-spinner spins the ball from leg to off side.
A bouncer is a short-pitched delivery aimed to rise towards the batsman's head or chest.
An appeal is when the fielding team asks the umpire to declare the batsman out.
A late cut is a shot played very late, using the pace of the ball to guide it behind point.
An umpire signals a six by raising both arms straight above their head.
An umpire signals a four by waving one arm back and forth horizontally.
A match with no result due to weather or other interruptions is called 'no result.'
